		<div id="comment_body_64848735"><p><div class="quote"><p>In my town I can drive copper-rich waste like this to my local recycling center and drop it in a big bin of ewaste (which gets "gleaned" by the locals before the authorities pick it up), but I can't put it in the recycling can and push it to the kerb. Recycling is so badly broken here.</p><p>But then I recently stayed at another person's home and saw what mixed up crap they put in their recycle bin, so the system doesn't really stand much of a chance</p></div><p>There's an incentive problem here. If I'm giving away my recycling for free, I have no incentive to properly sort paper from glass from copper from spoiled leftovers.</p><p>If the copper and gold in e-waste truly is valuable, more valuable than mining and refining new ore or industrial scale recycling when tearing down a building, surely someone will pay me for the e-waste. If no one is willing to buy it, perhaps recycling isn't as valuable as we think. Just toss it in the skip. At some future point, the landfill<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

